	<p>
		<term>Making a covalent bond</term>
	</p>

	<p>
		<term>Covalent compounds</term> are formed when atoms share electrons. When two electrons are shared between two atoms, this forms a <term>covalent bond</term>. Covalent bonds are quite strong and are difficult to break. Thus covalent compounds remain together as discrete units called <term>molecules</term>, even when dissolved, melted, or boiled.
	</p>

	<p>
		Before we discuss covalent compounds further, let’s learn rules that allow us to draw the Lewis dot structure for an atom:
	</p>

	<p><ol>
		<li>
			<p>
				Write the element symbol
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				Surround it with the <term>valence electrons</term> written as dots
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				There are 4 sides around the symbol (each side represents an outer shell atomic orbital-there is one outer s-orbital and 3 outer p-orbitals for most elements except hydrogen)
			</p>
		
			<p><ol>
				<li>
					<p>
						Place a maximum of 2 dots per side; don’t start pairing until you have to
					</p>
				</li>
		
				<li>
					<p>
						Which side does NOT matter
					</p>
				</li>
		
			</ol></p>
		</li>

	</ol></p>

	<p>
		How do covalent bonds form and how does sharing electrons help to hold together two atoms? Orbitals are most stable when they have completely filled (or completely empty orbitals). When two atoms come together, their atomic orbitals can combine together to form <term>molecular orbitals</term>. These molecular orbitals are shared between the two atoms and have shapes that resemble the s and p orbitals if they overlap with one another. Importantly, these are still orbitals, and thus molecular orbitals can still only hold 2 electrons.
	</p>

	<p>
		Recall from earlier this chapter that the most stable electron configuration for most atoms is 8 valence electrons, because 8 electrons is the number required to completely fill the outer shell s (one of them) and p (three of them) orbitals. This is called the <term>octet rule</term>. So how can we fulfill the octet rule without adding or removing electrons?
	</p>

	<p>
		We do this by forming molecular orbitals (which reduces the number of orbitals that have to be filled) and by sharing electrons between the atoms in these molecular orbitals. Consider the molecule <m>F_{2}</m>. Each fluorine has 7 valence electrons, for a total of 14 valence electrons. Each fluorine also has a 4 outer shell orbitals, one 2s orbital and three 2p orbitals, for a grand total of 8 outer shell orbitals. If two of those orbitals are combined into one molecular orbital, then the total number of outer shell orbitals is only 7. These 7 orbitals can be filled perfectly by the 14 electrons. Two of these electrons are shared between the two fluorine atoms in the molecular orbital and thus form the bond that links them together. See the figure below:
	</p>

	<figure>
	<image source="media/image1.png"/>
		<caption>A screenshot of a video game AI-generated content may be incorrect.</caption>
</figure>

	<p>
		The Lewis dot structures of 2 fluorine atoms are shown above. The circles are shown to emphasize the orbitals that the electrons are in. Note: normally a Lewis dot structure does NOT include these circles. In the bottom portion, the two fluorine atoms are joined together by a covalent bond. The red orbital is a molecular orbital that was created by fusing two atomic orbitals together. It contain electrons that came from both of the fluorine atoms.
	</p>

	<p>
		Hydrogen is an important common exception to the octet rule. The nearest noble gas to hydrogen is helium, which has a completely filled 1<sup>st</sup> shell that only requires two electrons. So hydrogen obeys the <term>duet rule</term> for valence electrons; it wants to have two valence electrons rather than 8.
	</p>

