	<p>
		<term>Lewis structures: Basic rules</term>
	</p>

	<p>
		When it comes to figuring out the structure of larger covalent molecules, the same principles apply (the octet rule, the duet rule, and combining atomic orbitals to form a shared molecular orbital). However, there are additional complexities that also get introduced. For instance, which atoms should be bound to which other atoms? Also, some atoms are capable of forming more than one bond. Carbon, for instance, has 4 valence electrons. That means that it needs 4 other electrons to be shared with it to reach its octet. That means that carbon likes to form 4 covalent bonds!
	</p>

	<p>
		To help facilitate drawing Lewis structures, there are some basic procedural steps that you should follow. We’ll begin with the basic rules and then increase the complexity with more rules in later sections.
	</p>

	<p>
		<em>Basic rules for Lewis structures of molecules:</em>
	</p>

	<p><ol>
		<li>
			<p>
				<em>Draw the skeleton structure. Arrange the atoms with atoms that can make more bonds (ex. C, N, O) in the center and atoms that can make fewer bonds on the outside (ex. H and halogens)</em>
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				<em>Count the total number of valence electrons. Add electrons for negative charges; subtract electrons for positive charges. Your final structure must have this number of electrons in it!!!</em>
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				<em>Form single bonds between the center atom and peripheral atoms. Remember that each bond is 2 electrons. Count how many electrons you have remaining</em>
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				<em>Place the remaining electrons around the outer atoms first and then the inner atoms until you have an octet (or duet) of electrons around each atom. Don’t forget that the bonds have 2 electrons!</em>
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				<em>More rules later…</em>
			</p>
		</li>

	</ol></p>

