	<p>
		<term>Lewis structures: Multiple bonds</term>
	</p>

	<p>
		Try to draw the Lewis structure of <m>O_{2}</m> (or see the figure below). If you follow the rules above, you quickly find that you have a problem, you can’t make an octet around each oxygen atom. How are we supposed to satisfy the octet rule, then?
	</p>

	<p>
		We can satisfy the octet rule on both atoms by joining two additional atomic orbitals to form a second molecular orbital and by using this additional molecular orbital to share another pair of electrons. This creates a double bond between the two oxygen atoms. Each bond is a separate molecular orbital that contains a pair of shared electrons.
	</p>

	<p>
		In some cases, such as when we try to draw the Lewis structure for <m>N_{2}</m>, we need to join still another pair of atomic orbitals to form a third molecular orbital that we can use to share a third pair of electrons. This creates a triple bond.
	</p>

	<p>
		The steps for drawing a Lewis structure can be added onto with an additional rule that covers these situations:
	</p>

	<p>
		<em>Basic rules for Lewis structures of molecules:</em>
	</p>

	<p><ol>
		<li>
			<p>
				<em>Draw the skeleton structure. Arrange the atoms with atoms that can make more bonds (ex. C, N, O) in the center and atoms that can make fewer bonds on the outside (ex. H and halogens)</em>
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				<em>Count the total number of valence electrons. Add electrons for negative charges; subtract electrons for positive charges. Your final structure must have this number of electrons in it!!!</em>
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				<em>Form single bonds between the center atom and peripheral atoms. Remember that each bond is 2 electrons. Count how many electrons you have remaining</em>
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				<em>Place the remaining electrons around the outer atoms first and then the inner atoms until you have an octet (or duet) of electrons around each atom. Don’t forget that the bonds have 2 electrons!</em>
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				<em>If any of the atoms don’t have an octet, then move a lone pair from an adjacent atom to make a 2<sup>nd</sup> bond between the atoms. This effectively adds to electrons to the receiving atom while keeping the electrons with the donor atom. Repeat this step as needed. You can form triple bonds, but you will never form a quadruple bond!</em>
			</p>
		</li>

	</ol></p>

